=== 9.3 Cross-Entropy Loss

==== The Formula

For a single prediction at position stem:[t]:

[stem]
++++
\mathcal{L}(t) = -\log P(t_{t+1} \mid t_1, \ldots, t_t)
++++

That's it.
Negative log of the probability assigned to the _true_ next token.

==== Why Negative Log?

The model outputs a probability stem:[p \in (0, 1\]].
We want a loss that is zero when the prediction is perfect (stem:[p = 1]), large when the model is wrong (stem:[p \to 0]), and differentiable everywhere.

stem:[-\log(p)] delivers all three:

[cols="1,1,2",options="header"]
|===
|Predicted probability stem:[p] |stem:[-\log(p)] |Interpretation
|1.00 |0.00 |Perfect
|0.80 |0.22 |Pretty good
|0.50 |0.69 |Random guess
|0.10 |2.30 |Mostly wrong
|0.01 |4.61 |Very wrong
|0.001 |6.91 |Catastrophically wrong
|===

[NOTE]
====
*Math Minute — Logarithms*

stem:[\log(p)] for stem:[p \in (0,1\]] is always stem:[\leq 0].
It passes through stem:[(1, 0)] and tends to stem:[-\infty] as stem:[p \to 0].
Because we negate it, stem:[-\log(p) \geq 0]: zero means perfect, large means wrong.
All modern ML uses natural log (base stem:[e]), so loss is measured in *nats*.
Using base 2 gives *bits*.
====

==== The Full Training Loss

A single document of length stem:[T] contributes:

[stem]
++++
\mathcal{L}_{\text{doc}} = \frac{1}{T} \sum_{t=1}^{T} -\log P(t_{t+1} \mid t_1, \ldots, t_t)
++++

==== Teacher Forcing

Notice the formula conditions on _true_ past tokens, not the model's _own predictions_.
This is called *teacher forcing*: during training, we always feed the ground-truth context.

This makes training stable, parallelizable, and simple.
The causal mask from Chapter 4 is what enables this — position stem:[t] can only attend to positions stem:[1 \ldots t], so the model's prediction at position stem:[t] is causally correct even when processing all positions in parallel.

==== Cross-Entropy as Information Theory

Cross-entropy has deep roots.
The *cross-entropy* between true stem:[q] and predicted stem:[p] is:

[stem]
++++
H(q, p) = -\sum_j q_j \log p_j
++++

When stem:[q] is one-hot, only the true token's term survives: stem:[H(q, p) = -\log p_{t_{t+1}}].
Exactly our loss.

*Minimizing cross-entropy is equivalent to minimizing the KL divergence between the model's predictions and the true data distribution.*
This is why cross-entropy is the natural loss for language models.
